Implement the private `take_first/4` helper used by `top/2` to walk the ETS
`:ordered_set` in key order and collect leaderboard entries.

`take_first(tid, key, n, acc)` recursively traverses the ordered-set table
`tid` starting at `key`, accumulating up to `n` results into `acc` (which holds
`{player_id, score}` tuples in reverse order). It must handle two stopping
conditions: when `key` is `:"$end_of_table"` (the traversal has run off the end
of the table) and when `n` has reached `0` (enough entries have been collected).
In either case it returns the accumulated results in correct leaderboard order,
i.e. `Enum.reverse(acc)`.

Otherwise, it looks up the row stored at `key` with `:ets.lookup/2` — each row
has the shape `{key, player_id, score}` — advances to the next key with
`:ets.next/2`, decrements `n` by one, and prepends `{player_id, score}` to the
accumulator before recursing. Because the composite key encodes score-descending
then arrival-ascending order, traversing keys in native ETS order yields the
final leaderboard order directly.

